e and other figures, Berlin argues, helped to shape twentieth-century nationalism, existentialism, democracy, totalitarianism, and our ideas about heroic individuals, self-fulfillment, and the exalted place of art. This new edition, illustrated for the first time, also features a new foreword by philosopher John Gray, in which he discusses Berlin's belief that the influence of romanticism has been unpredictable and contradictory in the extreme, fuelling anti-liberal political movements but also reinvigorating liberalism; a revised text; and a new appendix that includes some of Berlin's correspondence about the lectures and the reactions to them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aArts, Moderny18th century. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aAestheticism.  aAllegory.  aAnalogy.  aAnti-intellectualism.  aArt for art's sake.  aAugust Wilhelm Schlegel.  aAztec religion.  aBaron d'Holbach.  aBelles-lettres.  aCausality.  aCertainty.  aCivilisation (TV series).  aClassicism.  aConsciousness.  aContemporary art.  aDeism.  aDespotism.  aDynamism (metaphysics).  aEdward Burne-Jones.  aEpicureanism.  aEpigraph (literature).  aEthics.  aExistentialism.  aExplanation.  aFeeling.  aForm of life (philosophy).  aGenerosity.  aGiambattista Vico.  aGiorgio Vasari.  aGood and evil.  aHedonism.  aHenri Bergson.  aHerder.  aHumiliation.  aI Wish (manhwa).  aIdealism.  aImmanuel Kant.  aIrving Babbitt.  aIsaiah Berlin.  aItalian Renaissance.  aJohann Georg Hamann.  aJohann Joachim Winckelmann.  aLecture.  aLiberalism.  aLiterature.  aLord David Cecil.  aLutheranism.  aMagnificence (history of ideas).  aMario Praz.  aMaterialism.  aMelodrama.  aMorality.  aMoses Mendelssohn.  aNicholas Richardson.  aNihilism.  aNoble savage.  a